    {
      "step_id": "51a357af",
      "step_index": 4,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "hERG blockers commonly present:\n1) a **cationic center at physiological pH** (often a tertiary amine),\n2) **hydrophobic/aromatic \u201cwings\u201d** that bind into hydrophobic regions of the channel cavity,\n3) an overall **shape/length** that fits the cavity and enables \u03c0/hydrophobic interactions (notably with residues like Tyr/Phe in the pore region).",
      "tool_name": null,
      "tool_input": null,
      "tool_output": null,
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T19:49:29.497195+00:00"
    },
    {
      "step_id": "2d980f23",
      "step_index": 5,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "For this molecule:\n- **Cationic center:** likely **weak/atypical**. Exocyclic amines can be protonated, but they are attached to **electron-poor heteroaromatic rings**, often reducing basicity and increasing H-bonding/solvation. Lack of a **single, well-positioned, lipophilic tertiary amine** reduces canonical hERG pharmacophore matching.\n- **Hydrophobic/aromatic domains:** the \u201cwings\u201d are **heteroaryl rings with multiple nitrogens and amino substituents**, which are **less hydrophobic and less \u03c0-rich** than phenyl/indole systems commonly seen in hERG blockers. This tends to reduce favorable hydrophobic/\u03c0 interactions in the channel.\n- **Polarity/PSA:** very high (many nitrogens). High polarity generally **reduces membrane partitioning** and reduces occupancy of the largely hydrophobic binding cavity, decreasing hERG risk.\n- **Length/shape:** the butyl linker gives some length, but the ends are **polar heteroaryls**, so even if the shape could fit, the interaction energy in the hydrophobic cavity is likely unfavorable.",
      "tool_name": null,
      "tool_input": null,
      "tool_output": null,
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T19:49:29.497217+00:00"
    },
    {
      "step_id": "39dc5845",
      "step_index": 6,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "## 3) Mechanistic basis (interaction with hERG)",
      "tool_name": null,
      "tool_input": null,
      "tool_output": null,
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T19:49:29.497239+00:00"
    },
    {
      "step_id": "6fc7a952",
      "step_index": 7,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "Typical hERG blockade involves:\n- **Electrostatic attraction** between a **protonated amine** and polar residues, plus\n- **\u03c0-stacking / hydrophobic contacts** with aromatic residues in the central cavity.",
      "tool_name": null,
      "tool_input": null,
      "tool_output": null,
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T19:49:29.497260+00:00"
    },
    {
      "step_id": "8828b625",
      "step_index": 8,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "This molecule is more consistent with:\n- **Strong solvation and H-bonding to water** competing against binding in the channel cavity.\n- If protonated, it may carry charge, but the **charge is not embedded in a lipophilic environment** (as in many hERG ligands), which usually weakens binding to the hydrophobic pocket.\n- The heteroaryl rings are **electron-poor**, typically giving weaker \u03c0 interactions than phenyl-rich systems.",
